Introduction

Prostate cancer is a leading cause of male cancer-related death. One characteristic of prostate cancer is persistent AR (androgen receptor) signaling, where AR is a nuclear steroid hormone receptor which acts as a transcription factor to upregulate multiple genes responsible for cancer growth. p300 and CBP are paralogous, highly conserved proteins that are potent co-activators of AR signaling.

A recent study tested the efficacy of CCS1477, a novel small-molecule inhibitor of the p300/CBP conserved bromodomain, as a potential therapeutic agent for treating lethal prostate cancer (de Bono et al., 2021)[1]. The study uses 22Rv1 (human prostate carcinoma epithelial cell line) where 3 samples are treated with CCS1477, and 3 are controls1.

There is another set of 3 samples where the cells are treated with JQ1, a known bromodomain protein inhibitor. These are excluded for this assignment, since it is mentioned that “samples treated with JQ1 or CCS1477 displayed a high degree of separation after PCA, suggesting that these samples have distinct transcriptional alterations after drug treatment”.

Prostate cancer research is of personal interest to me since one of my grandfathers passed away from prostate cancer in 2011. Through this assignment, my goal is to better understand how bioinformatics is used to study novel cancer therapeutics 2.

# translate counts into "counts per million" using the edgeR package function cpm
cpms = edgeR::cpm(p300_CBP_exp[,7:12])
rownames(cpms) <- p300_CBP_exp[,1]

# In edgeR, the standard is to remove features without at least 1 cpm
# in n of the samples, where n = size of the smallest group of replicates
# For this study, n = 3
keep = rowSums(cpms >1) >=3
p300_CBP_exp_filtered = p300_CBP_exp[keep,]
dim(p300_CBP_exp_filtered)
## [1] 15790    15

Check for outliers

data2plot <- log2(edgeR::cpm(p300_CBP_exp_filtered[,7:12]))
boxplot(data2plot, xlab = "Samples", ylab = "log2 CPM",
las = 2, cex = 0.5, cex.lab = 0.5,
cex.axis = 0.5, main = "p300_CBP RNASeq Samples")

#draw the median on each box plot
abline(h = median(apply(data2plot, 2, median)), col = "green", lwd = 0.6, lty = "dashed")

The Warning message says boxplot 1 contained an outlier. However, there is no well-founded reason to believe a measurement error has occurred, which would justify their removal. Instead of removing them, the presence of outliers is reported here as a potential confounding variable 4.

Dispersion

# Checking the dispersion of our data
model_design <- model.matrix(~samples$replicate 
                             + samples$cell_type+0)  # define a model first
d <- edgeR::estimateDisp(d, model_design)
edgeR::plotBCV(d,col.tagwise = "black",col.common = "red",)

It shows the general trend where low counts have higher dispersion. Here’s an alternative plot that shows the same trend:

edgeR::plotMeanVar(d, show.raw.vars = TRUE,
            show.tagwise.vars=TRUE,
            NBline=TRUE, show.ave.raw.vars = TRUE,
            show.binned.common.disp.vars = TRUE)

Apply Normalization

First, determine the shape of our data:

counts_density <- apply(log2(edgeR::cpm(p300_CBP_exp_filtered[,7:12])),
2, density)
#calculate the limits across all the samples
xlim <- 0; ylim <- 0
for (i in 1:length(counts_density)) {
xlim <- range(c(xlim, counts_density[[i]]$x));
ylim <- range(c(ylim, counts_density[[i]]$y))
}
cols <- rainbow(length(counts_density))
ltys <- rep(1, length(counts_density))

#plot the first density plot to initialize the plot
plot(counts_density[[1]], xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, type="n",
ylab="Smoothing density of log2-CPM",
main="", cex.lab = 0.85)

#plot each line
for (i in 1:length(counts_density)) {lines(counts_density[[i]], col=cols[i], lty=ltys[i])}
#create legend
legend("topright", colnames(data2plot),
col=cols, lty=ltys, cex=0.75,
border ="blue", text.col = "green4",
merge = TRUE, bg = "gray90")

Although this is not a perfect normal distribution, for our purposes, TMM (Trimmed Mean of M-values) should suffice:

# perform normalization

Map to HUGO symbols

# ID mapping - from ensembl to HUGO symbol
ensembl <- useMart("ensembl")
ensembl <- useDataset("hsapiens_gene_ensembl",mart=ensembl)

# convert the IDs (first, check if conversion was done previously)
conversion_stash <- "p300_CBP_id_conversion.rds"
if(file.exists(conversion_stash)){
  p300_CBP_id_conversion <- readRDS(conversion_stash)
} else {
  p300_CBP_id_conversion <- getBM(attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id","hgnc_symbol"),
                            filters = c("ensembl_gene_id"),
                            values = p300_CBP_exp_filtered$Geneid,
                            mart = ensembl)
  saveRDS(p300_CBP_id_conversion, conversion_stash)
}

# result: num.genes we were able to map
length(which(rownames(normalized_counts) %in% 
                p300_CBP_id_conversion$ensembl_gene_id))
## [1] 15326
# how many did we miss?

                p300_CBP_id_conversion$ensembl_gene_id))

Conclusion & Outlook

From the raw data, low-counts were removed but the outliers were kept. Normalizing the data led to better alignment of distributions. Not all ensembl IDs could be mapped to HUGO symbols, which meant about 10% (1,328 out of 15,790) of rows had to be removed. The dataset is now ready for further analysis in assignement 2.
